can best grasp the increasingly murky line between “the criminal” and “the political” with a “politics of living” that casts slum and state in opposition to one another. Living Politics shows us how legitimate domains of politics are redefined, how state sovereignty is forcibly enacted, and how the production of new citizen identities crystallize at the intersections of race, gender, and class.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCommunity organizationzSouth Africa. 0aCommunity organization-South Africa. 0aEnvironmental degradationxPolitical aspectszSouth Africa. 0aEnvironmental degradation-Political aspects-South Africa. 0aPolitical activistszSouth Africa. 0aPolitical activists-South Africa. 0aSouth Africa-Politics and government-1994-. 0aSquatter settlementszSouth Africa. 0aSquatter settlements-South Africa. 0aSquattersxPolitical activityzSouth Africa. 0aSquatters-Political activity-South Africa. 0aUrban poorxPolitical activityzSouth Africa. 0aUrban poor-Political activity-South Africa. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aSouth Africa.  acities.  acitizenship.  aenvironment.  agender.  agovernance.  apolitics.  apoverty.  arace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z97831106385160 cprintz978022651952440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226519838423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226519838/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles